Dark-bellied Brent Geese   Branta bernicla   in relation to lemming cycles  Relationships between variations of the land-ocean-atmosphere system of northeastern Asia and northwestern North America  Temporal and geographic variation in survival of juvenile Black Brant  Aerial photographic survey of brant colonies on the Yukon-Kuskokwim Delta, Alaska  Dynamics of avian populations may be governed by a complex interaction between immediate effects of predation and longer-term trophic feedbacks between individuals and their foods. We used a long-term study of uniquely marked Black Brant geese (  Branta bernicla  nigricans ) to estimate recruitment into the breeding population. We related recruitment to nest success, which directly affects recruitment 2 to 3 years later. We also assessed similarly time-lagged relationships between recruitment and number of nests in the colony, a measure of local density, and pre-fledging and first-year survival, the latter of which is strongly influenced by growth conditions and food availability for young of the year. We assessed relationships between number of recruits and explanatory variables in 2 sets of models, which either included or excluded a linear trend across years in numbers of recruits. The best-performing models in each model set explained a substantial proportion of the variation in numbers of recruits 2 to 3 years later (85 and 78&percnt; in the 2 model sets, respectively). First-year survival was an important predictor of number of recruits in both sets of models, whereas nest success was important only in models lacking a trend across years. Number of nests in the colony had a relatively weak negative association with number of recruits. First-year survival reflects a lagged response to earlier nest-predation events. Reduced grazing during predation events can result in loss of grazing lawns and thus reduced growth rates of future cohorts of goslings, which are regulated by food abundance and density of broods. Our finding that recruitment is insufficient to maintain the breeding population results from both direct effect of predation on nests, primarily by Arctic foxes (  Alopex lagopus  ), and longer-term indirect effects of such predation on first-year survival of Black Brant.  Las din&aacute;micas poblacionales de las aves pueden estar gobernadas por un interacci&oacute;n compleja entre los efectos inmediatos de la depredaci&oacute;n y los efectos de largo plazo de la retroalimentaci&oacute;n tr&oacute;fica entre los individuos y su alimento. Usamos un estudio de largo plazo de gansos   Branta bernicla  nigricans  marcados individualmente para estimar el reclutamiento de la poblaci&oacute;n reproductiva. Relacionamos el reclutamiento con el &eacute;xito de los nidos, el cual afecta directamente el reclutamiento dos a tres a&ntilde;os despu&eacute;s. De forma similar, determinamos el desfase temporal en la relaci&oacute;n entre el reclutamiento y el n&uacute;mero de nidos en la colonia, una medida de densidad local y la supervivencia durante el pre-emplumamiento y el primer a&ntilde;o; esta &uacute;ltima se ve fuertemente influenciada por las condiciones durante el crecimiento y la disponibilidad de alimento para los polluelos del a&ntilde;o. Determinamos las relaciones entre el n&uacute;mero de aves reclutadas y las variables explicativas en dos modelos que inclu&iacute;an o exclu&iacute;an una tendencia lineal en el n&uacute;mero de reclutas a trav&eacute;s de los a&ntilde;os. Los mejores modelos explicaron una proporci&oacute;n sustancial de la variaci&oacute;n en el n&uacute;mero de aves reclutadas dos a tres a&ntilde;os despu&eacute;s (85&percnt; y 78&percnt; en los dos modelos, respectivamente). La supervivencia del primer a&ntilde;o fue un predictor importante del n&uacute;mero de reclutas en ambos modelos mientas que el &eacute;xito de los nidos s&oacute;lo fue importante en los modelos que no inclu&iacute;an la tendencia a trav&eacute;s de los a&ntilde;os. El n&uacute;mero de los nidos en la colonia tuvo una asociaci&oacute;n negativa relativamente d&eacute;bil con el n&uacute;mero de aves reclutadas. La supervivencia del primer a&ntilde;o refleja una respuesta retrasada a los eventos de depredaci&oacute;n anteriores. La reducci&oacute;n en el ramoneo durante los eventos de depredaci&oacute;n puede resultar en la p&eacute;rdida de las &aacute;reas de pastoreo. Tales p&eacute;rdidas reducen las tasas de crecimiento de las cohortes futuras de polluelos, que est&aacute;n reguladas por la abundancia del alimento y la densidad de las nidadas. Nuestro hallazgo de la insuficiencia del reclutamiento para mantener la poblaci&oacute;n reproductiva resulta tanto de los efectos directos de la depredaci&oacute;n en los nidos principalmente por zorros   Alopex lagopus   como de los efectos indirectos a largo plazo de la depredaci&oacute;n en la supervivencia del primer a&ntilde;o de  B. b. nigricans .   Palabras clave:  Alopex lagopus  ,   Branta bernicla  nigricans,  cascada tr&oacute;fica, depredaci&oacute;n, din&aacute;micas poblaiconales, &eacute;xito de los nidos, ramoneo, reclutamiento, supervivencia, zorro &aacute;rtico  Population dynamics in species with high adult survival rates are typically governed primarily by variation in recruitment because adult survival is largely conserved, even though finite rate of population increase, &lambda;, is usually most sensitive to adult survival (Stearns 1992,  Festa-Bianchet et al. 1998 ,  Cooch et al. 2001 ). Exceptions may exist for species subjected to human harvest if harvest rates affect adult survival sufficiently to influence &lambda; ( Sedinger et al. 2007 ,  Brodie et al. 2013 ,  P&eacute;ron 2013 ). Presumably, when nonhuman predation on adults is sufficiently high, it may influence population dynamics ( Owen-Smith and Mason 2005 ,  Johnson et al. 2013 ).  Variation in recruitment is the principal mechanism by which density-dependent feedbacks are manifest in populations of long-lived species ( Gaillard et al. 1998 ,  Cooch et al. 2001 ). Density dependence commonly operates directly through availability of food for young (e.g.,  Cooch et al. 2001 ,  Sedinger et al. 1998 ,  2001 ). When density dependence is less important, however, predation can play an important role in population regulation. In birds, nest predation is the most conspicuous predation mechanism ( MacDonald and Bolton 2008 ), and declines in numerous avian populations have been attributed to predation on nests and young ( Newton 1998 ).  For herbivores (e.g., geese), effects of predation and density dependence are frequently negatively associated because predation reduces grazing of vegetation, with associated positive effects on food supply ( Krebs 2009 ). Such effects, however, can be complex; reduced grazing clearly has the potential to increase food availability in the short term ( Sedinger et al. 2001 ). Numerous species of grazers maintain grazing lawns in which plants are more nutritious than in surrounding areas ( Bazely and Jefferies 1986 ), and reduced grazing pressure can result in loss of grazing lawns ( McNaughton 1985 ,  Person et al. 2003 ,  Archibald 2008 ). Because availability of highly nutritious plants may limit productive processes (e.g., growth;  Sedinger 1984 ,  1997 ,  Barboza et al. 2009 ), the condition of grazing lawns may influence these productive processes ( Sedinger et al. 2001 ,  Nicolai and Sedinger 2012b ). Thus, reduced grazing due to higher predation rates might reduce grazing lawns, resulting in lagged reductions in growth and recruitment.  Several species of Arctic-nesting geese maintain such grazing lawns, which are vital for growth of their offspring during the short Arctic summer ( Hik et al. 1991 ,  Person et al. 2003 ,  Lake et al. 2008 ). Growth rates of goslings are directly related to food abundance ( Cooch et al. 1993 ,  Lepage et al. 1998 ,  Sedinger et al. 2001 ), and growth largely governs survival during the first year ( Owen and Black 1989 ,  Cooch et al. 1993 ,  Sedinger and Chelgren 2007 ). Thus, areal extent of grazing lawns and biomass of vegetation on grazing lawns directly influence recruitment of goslings into the breeding population ( Herzog 2002 ,  Sedinger and Nicolai 2011 ).  Predation by Arctic foxes on goose nests reduces grazing activity in the current year because, following loss of their nests, adult geese undergo molt migrations to distant locations ( Owen 1980 ,  Bollinger and Derksen 1996 ) and do not graze vegetation near colonies. Consequently, in years of high nest predation rates, areal extent of grazing lawns is reduced because sedges in grazing lawns &ldquo;revert&rdquo; to an ungrazed, taller, and less nutritious morph ( Sedinger and Raveling 1984 ,  Person et al. 2003 ). Thus, predation reduces recruitment immediately through reduced numbers of offspring produced and in future years by reducing food required for gosling growth and survival. The lagged negative effects of predation on recruitment mean that relatively rare predation events can lead to lower recruitment rates inadequate to balance mortality, resulting in population declines for extended periods following such predation events.  We used a long-term study of individually marked Black Brant geese on the Yukon-Kuskokwim Delta (YKD) of western Alaska, where colonies have declined since at least the early 1980s ( Sedinger et al. 1993 ,  Wilson 2012 ), to assess both direct and indirect roles of predation on recruitment into the breeding population. Specifically, we assessed the effects of colony size, nest success, pre-fledging survival, and first-year (post-fledging) survival to understand the immediate role of predation vs. its delayed effects operating through changes in grazing lawns. This study complements earlier work describing long-term patterns in adult and juvenile survival ( Sedinger et al. 2007 ,  Sedinger and Nicolai 2011 ,  Nicolai and Sedinger 2012b ) and improves understanding of the relative roles of changes in survival vs. recruitment in the population decline of a long-lived herbivore during the past 4 decades.    Black Brant nest primarily colonially from the YKD in southwestern Alaska along the Pacific coast of North America to the central Canadian Arctic and on Banks and Victoria islands ( Lewis et al. 2014 ). Black Brant also nest along the Siberian coast from approximately the Bering Strait to the Lena River Delta ( Lewis et al. 2014 ). Historically, &gt;70&percnt; of the Black Brant breeding population nested on the YKD ( Sedinger et al. 1993 ,  Lewis et al. 2014 ), where &sim;80&percnt; nested in 4 major colonies, each ranging from 4,000 to 8,000 nests, with remaining nests in smaller aggregations ( Sedinger et al. 1993 ,  Wilson 2012 ). Colonies occur within &sim;2 km of the Bering Sea coast in tidally influenced coastal ecosystems, dominated by grass and sedge communities ( Sedinger et al. 1993 ,  Jorgenson 2000 ). Some nests (typically &lt;10&percnt;) have been flooded by high tides during the nesting period in May&ndash;June up to 3 times per decade (A. W. VanDellen personal communication); more extensive flooding, destroying about 40&percnt; of nests, has occurred twice since 1950 (1966 and 1972; C. Lensink personal communication). Immediately following hatch, Black Brant lead their broods to rearing areas within 40 km of their breeding colonies ( Flint et al. 1995 ,  Lake et al. 2008 ). Rearing areas consist of graminoid meadows with grazing lawns of   Carex subspathacea   along borders of mudflats and pond margins ( Jorgenson 2000 ). We conducted this study from 1987 to 2006 at the Tutakoke River colony (TRC; 61&deg;N, 165&deg;W) on the central Bering Sea coast of the YKD. Before 2000, the TRC represented about 20&percnt; of the entire Black Brant breeding population.  The 2 most important predators on nests of Black Brant during our study were Arctic foxes and Glaucous Gulls (  Larus hyperboreus  ;  Strang 1977 ,  Anthony et al. 1991 ). Glaucous Gulls nested within the Black Brant colony in small numbers (&lt;50 nests annually), and low-level predation on nests was relatively constant, although predation on goslings was substantial ( Bowman et al. 2004 ). No quantitative data exist on numbers of Arctic foxes present on the YKD, although we can infer general patterns of abundance from historical accounts and patterns of nest predation. Predation by Arctic foxes on goose nests was not observed by investigators in the coastal zone of the YKD before 1976 ( Conover 1926 ,  Brandt 1943 ,  Olson 1951 ,  Shepherd 1963 ), although indigenous residents indicated Arctic foxes were present in the region ( Olson 1951 ).  Eisenhauer (1977)  first reported Arctic foxes at TRC in 1976, observing them 4 times in 427 hr from an elevated observation tower. Nest success averaged 80&percnt; at TRC during 15 field seasons between 1950 and 1982 and was as low as 60&percnt; during only 2 years, when tidal flooding destroyed substantial numbers of nests. Irruptions of Arctic foxes resulted in destruction of &gt;80&percnt; of nests at TRC in 1982, 1984, 1985, and again in 2001 and 2003 ( Anthony et al. 1991 ; J. S. Sedinger personal communication). Arctic foxes also destroyed substantial numbers, but &lt;50&percnt;, of nests in 1994, 1997, 2004, and 2008. Most egg predation by Glaucous Gulls at TRC resulted in partial loss of the clutch, not complete destruction of nests, and Glaucous Gulls never accounted for predation in &gt;6&percnt; ( x̄  &equals; 2&percnt;) of nests. Furthermore, proportion of predation attributable to Glaucous Gulls was negatively correlated with the proportion of nests that failed ( r  &equals; &minus;0.5,  P  &equals; 0.012), indicating that gulls were not the principal predator during years of high nest predation (J. S. Sedinger personal communication).  Small numbers of Arctic foxes are capable of destroying large numbers of nests because they cache, rather than immediately consume, eggs and thus are not satiated ( Stickney 1991 ,  Samelius et al. 2007 ).  Stickney (1991)  estimated that a single Arctic fox was capable of removing 60 eggs (15 nests) per day, or 390 nests during a 26-day incubation period, of Black Brant. Thus, 10 Arctic foxes could destroy all of the nests in a Black Brant colony containing 3,900 nests. Nonbreeding Arctic foxes are especially effective predators of Black Brant eggs because they are not tied to den sites and are free to forage throughout the nesting colonies ( Anthony et al. 1991 ,  Anthony 1997 ). Arctic foxes on the YKD depend on high tundra vole (  Microtus oeconomus  ) numbers to breed ( Anthony et al. 2000 ), which results in low predation rates by Arctic foxes when tundra vole numbers are high, likely associated with the spatial separation of den sites from the breeding colony. Because tundra voles on the YKD do not cycle regularly ( Fischer and Stehn 2011 ; J. S. Sedinger personal observation), Arctic foxes and associated predation on nests are not cyclic as they have been in the Palearctic ( Summers 1986 ,  Ebbinge and Spaans 2002 ) and eastern Canadian Arctic ( B&ecirc;ty et al. 2002 ).  We annually searched for Black Brant nests on 49 plots, 100 m in diameter, randomly placed throughout TRC. We began searching plots when &sim;10&percnt; of nests had been initiated. Each plot was searched every 4 days until egg laying was complete, then all nests were checked again immediately before hatch began and again after hatch was complete. A subsample of these nests was associated with individually marked adults (discussed later) and, once hatch began, these nests were visited on alternate days until they hatched. This protocol provided a sample of nests monitored on a regular schedule from egg laying until their fates were determined. We estimated apparent nest success from this sample of nests. We also searched the entire colony and attempted to locate all nests associated with at least one marked adult by flushing females from their nests and checking their legs for tarsal bands. All nonplot nests were visited on alternate days as hatch approached to check for pipping eggs, indicating hatch. We applied uniquely numbered webtags ( Alliston 1975 ,  Flint et al. 1995 ) to as many goslings as possible on their hatch day in all nests both on and off plots, associated with a marked adult both on and off plots.  We captured both adults and goslings in mid-July during the adult wing molt by herding them into corral traps ( Sedinger et al. 1997 ). We determined sex by cloacal examination ( Owen 1980 ), and individuals received a steel U.S. Geological Survey band and a 2.5 cm tall plastic band, engraved with a unique 3-character code. We released all individuals together following processing. In some large banding drives, some individuals were moved directly from the capture pen to the holding pen during the banding operation to reduce the time the entire group was held. These individuals were moved to the release pen throughout processing and were not excluded based on any criteria, so we do not believe any bias was introduced by this practice. We recorded the number of individuals of each age class released without bands and all previously marked individuals recaptured during banding.  where  n ij   was the number of banded recruits of age  i  encountered nesting in year  j ;  &rho; (j-k)   was the proportion of goslings captured  k  years earlier that had received bands; and  p̂ b(j-k)   was the probability of capturing a gosling  k  years before year  j  (from  Nicolai and Sedinger 2012a ),  p̂ nj   was the probability of encountering a breeding female conditioned on that female nesting (from analyses for  Nicolai and Sedinger 2012b ), and 0.67 was the probability that a 2- or 3-year-old female nested ( Sedinger et al. 2008 ). The latter 2 parameters were based on robust design analyses ( Kendall et al. 1997 ). We calculated per capita recruitment as the ratio of recruits to nests in a given year.   Nicolai and Sedinger (2012a)  developed encounter histories for goslings webtagged in the nest based on encounters of the webtags themselves to minimize bias associated with individuals receiving a visible band during their first summer. Consequently, they did not use encounters based on observation of engraved tarsal bands. Because webtags required physical capture to encounter and first-year survival was generally low, we recorded encounters of relatively small numbers of webtags following each gosling's first summer. Therefore, all such encounters were pooled to create the third encounter occasion necessary to estimate survival from hatching to fledging or pre-fledging survival ( Lebreton et al. 1992 ). This analysis also produced annual estimates of the probability of capturing goslings in banding drives, which we used in the calculation of the number of new recruits.  Estimates of age-specific probability of breeding for 2- and 3-year olds were from a robust design CMR analysis of encounters of breeding Black Brant during nesting and banding drives ( Sedinger et al. 2008 ). The robust design uses patterns of encounters among secondary occasions (nesting and banding drives, during which the population is assumed to be closed;  Kendall et al. 1997 ) within primary occasions, which for Black Brant was the entire breeding season. Robust design produces estimates of (1) the probability of being present, synonymous with breeding in this study ( Sedinger et al. 2001 ), and (2) encounter probabilities conditioned on individuals being present during a primary occasion ( Kendall et al. 1997 ). We used both kinds of parameters in estimates of the number of new recruits.  We used estimates of both pre-fledging and first-year (post-fledging) survival as explanatory variables in the analysis of numbers of new recruits to TRC. Estimates of first-year survival were based on Cormack-Jolly-Seber models of encounters of individual goslings captured and released during banding drives ( Lebreton et al. 1992 ,  Nicolai and Sedinger 2012a ). Nicolai and Sedinger (2102a) produced estimates of first-year survival for each brood-rearing area from which marked goslings were released (see details on both kinds of survival estimates in  Nicolai and Sedinger 2012a ). We calculated weighted colony-wide means of pre-fledging survival and first-year survival estimates for each year, where the weights were the inverse of the variances of the survival estimates from each brood-rearing area, and we used these means in models predicting number of recruits. We provide annual mean (&plusmn;SE) estimates of pre-fledging and first-year survival in Appendix A.  U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has annually estimated numbers of nests in 4 major Black Brant colonies on the YKD using aerial videography since 1992, except in 1996 due to logistical problems ( Anthony et al. 1995 ,  Wilson 2012 ).  Wilson (2012)  provides detail about the methodology, which we describe briefly here. Numbers of nests were estimated by counting Black Brant nests in images generated by digital cameras along systematically placed transects within each colony. A sample of images was ground-truthed annually to estimate detection and error rates. Approximately 10&percnt; of each colony was sampled annually, except in 1996 when no survey was flown. We used the average of numbers of nests for 1995 and 1997 to produce an estimate of number of nests for 1996.  The L-P estimator assumed that the population was closed between the 2 samples. This assumption may be relaxed, as long as both marked and unmarked individuals have the same probability of leaving the population between the first and second samples, in which case the population size (number of nests in our case) at the time of the first sample is estimated ( Otis et al. 1978 ).  We also used estimates of apparent nest success (number of nests hatched/number of nests monitored on plots) as an explanatory variable for numbers of recruits. Apparent estimates of nest success can overestimate nest success ( Johnson 1979 ). Bias results primarily from (1) underestimates of numbers of failed nests and (2) reduced exposure to failure in samples discovered during incubation. Black Brant nests were conspicuous, and we generated samples from plots where we found all nests during egg laying. Thus, bias should have been minimal and relatively constant. Because our goal in this study was to assess variation in recruitment and factors affecting recruitment, we believe some bias in our estimates of nest success is acceptable.  We calculated the average of each explanatory variable (e.g., nest success) for 2 and 3 years before the year of recruitment because our estimate of recruitment included 2- and 3-year-olds nesting for the first time. We standardized the response variable and each explanatory variable by subtracting the mean and dividing by the standard deviation so all variables were on the same scale. We have observed declining long-term trends in numbers of recruits, nest success, and both pre-fledging and first-year survival of Black Brant ( Nicolai and Sedinger 2012a ). Although it is biologically plausible that trends in recruits and explanatory variables were causally related, we cannot rule out the possibility that the common trend among variables represented a spurious relationship with another variable we did not consider. We thus considered 2 sets of models. One set included the following explanatory variables in candidate models: number of nests in the TRC, nest success, pre-fledging survival, and first-year survival. We also included a quadratic term for number of nests to allow for nonlinear density effects of numbers of nests. The second model set included all of the explanatory variables from the first set plus a term allowing for a linear trend across years. Although this second model set potentially provided an overly conservative assessment of the effects of explanatory variables, it protected against the potential for spurious covariation among variables through time and allowed an assessment of the residual effects of the explanatory variables on annual variation in numbers of recruits after controlling for the effects of long-term trends.  We used linear models with an identity link and assuming a Gaussian error distribution in R ( R Core Team 2013 ) to assess models of variation in annual number of recruits. We considered all potential additive combinations of explanatory variables (linear and quadratic terms for number of nests at TRC, nest success, pre-fledging survival, and first-year survival) and a subset of their pairwise interactions in candidate models. Number of nests provided a measure of local density, which can influence food availability ( Herzog 2002 ). We included interactions between number of nests and nest success because the product of the 2 governed density of broods. We included an interaction between nest success and first-year survival because in years of high nest success, more broods were present on rearing areas, thereby reducing food availability, growth rates, and first-year survival ( Herzog 2002 ,  Sedinger and Chelgren 2007 ). We use Akaike's Information Criterion adjusted for small sample size (AICc) to assess performance of models and Akaike weights ( w i  ) to assess the strength of evidence for the influence of individual variables on recruitment. We used  Cade's (2015)  approach for producing model-averaged parameter estimates and conditional confidence intervals, which accounts for correlation among explanatory variables in linear models. We report model-averaged coefficients and 85&percnt; confidence intervals for parameter estimates, consistent with an information theoretic approach to model selection ( Arnold 2010 ). We also used the cor and pcor.test (ppcor package) functions in R to estimate correlations and partial correlations, controlled for year, among variables, respectively.    We monitored 6,196 nests ( x̄  &equals; 282 annually) for nest success. Apparent nest success ranged from 0.16 to 0.89 between 1987 and 2004 ( Figure 1 ). Estimates of pre-fledging and first-year survival were based on release of 17,388 webtagged goslings and 21,941 goslings near fledging ( Nicolai and Sedinger 2012a ). Pre-fledging survival ranged from 0 in 2001 to 0.40 in 1999, whereas first-year survival ranged from 0 in 2001 to 0.85 in 1987 ( Nicolai and Sedinger 2012a ; Appendix A). Number of nests at TRC ranged from 885 in 1987 to 7,437 nests in 2000, with numbers generally increasing during the1990s but declining since 2000 ( Figure 2 ). We estimated that 4,283 2- and 3-year-old recruits (ranging from 27 in 2004 to 852 in 1990) entered the breeding population at TRC between 1987 and 2006. Number of recruits declined from 852 in 1990 to 27 in 2004 and has been &lt;10&percnt; of nests at TRC every year since 1993 ( Figure 3  and  4 ).  Annual estimates of apparent nest success of Black Brant nests on the Tutakoke River colony, Alaska, 1987&minus;2004, used to estimate number of recruits from 1990 to 2006. Sample sizes are indicated above each estimate.  Number of Black Brant nests on the Tutakoke River colony, Alaska, 1987&ndash;2006. Estimates for 1987&minus;1991 were based on Lincoln-Petersen estimates, and estimates after 1991 were based on aerial videography of random strips throughout the colony (see Methods). We used number of nests 1987&minus;2004 as an explanatory variable in models of recruitment and numbers of nests 1990&minus;2006 to compare against number of recruits. No estimate was available for 1996 due to logistical problems.  Estimated number of 2- and 3-year-old female recruits into the breeding population of Black Brant geese nesting on the Tutakoke River colony, Alaska, 1990&minus;2006. Estimates were based on the observed number of female recruits, adjusted for the proportion of each cohort marked, proportion of individuals examined during the recru