iological linkage between the explanatory variables we considered and number of recruits; thus, we argue that controlling for the long-term trend in explanatory variables and number of recruits produces a conservative assessment of the relationships between the two. Controlling for a trend across years depends on the assumption that some suite of variables we did not consider simultaneously explains the decline in both number of recruits and explanatory variables ( Table 1 ) while weakening the relationship between these explanatory variables and number of recruits. Our data were not the result of a controlled experiment, so we cannot rule out the existence of such a suite of variables, but we believe such a hypothesis is less plausible than direct influences of the variables we considered on recruitment.  Grazing lawns, which regulate growth ( Sedinger et al. 2001 ,  Herzog 2002 ,  Lake et al. 2008 ) and therefore first-year survival of goslings ( Sedinger and Chelgren 2007 ), are maintained by grazing by the geese themselves ( Person et al. 2003 ; R. W. Ruess personal communication). After 3 years of intense predation by Arctic foxes on nests at TRC in 1983&minus;1985 (nest success &lt;10&percnt;;  Anthony et al. 1991 ), areal extent of grazing lawn was still increasing on brood-rearing areas associated with TRC in 1998 ( Person et al. 2003 ). Mass of goslings at fledging tracked this increase in grazing lawn extent ( Person et al. 2003 ), resulting in increased first-year survival and recruitment. Gosling mass during this period, however, remained well below the potential if more food had been available; Black Brant goslings from Alaska's Arctic coast, where food biomass was higher, were about 50&percnt; heavier at fledging during this period ( Sedinger et al. 2001 ) and experienced higher first-year survival ( Ward et al. 2004 ). The evidence thus suggests that after 3 years of high predation rates on nests in the early 1980s, grazing lawns had still not been fully restored by 1998, more than a decade later.  The complex relationships among predation, grazing, and extent of grazing lawns creates the potential for substantial time lags in the relationship between goose density and food abundance. In the short term (a single breeding season) following a predation event, density exceeds carrying capacity, and growth of goslings is reduced, resulting in lower first-year survival and lower recruitment. Annual grazing, however, slowly increases the extent of grazing lawn and the number of broods that can be supported for up to a decade following major predation events ( Person et al. 2003 ). Our understanding of this dynamic is currently not sufficient to predict the response to the more moderate reductions in nest success during the 1990s (1994, 1995, 1997), but we believe the destruction of most nests at TRC in 2001 and 2003 was sufficient to have again produced major losses of grazing lawn. Visual inspection of brood rearing areas near TRC during 2006&minus;2010 indicates substantial reductions in grazing lawn compared to the late-1990s (J. S. Sedinger personal observation).  We have emphasized lagged negative effects of predation on grazing lawns and the resulting negative effects on growth and survival of goslings. Earlier work on the TRC Black Brant population suggests that slow growth can also reduce the probability that individuals breed ( Sedinger et al. 1995 ,  2004 ). Thus, reduced numbers of recruits could also reflect a smaller proportion of fledged goslings that enter the breeding population even if they survive.  Annual survival of adult female Black Brant has averaged 89&percnt; since the 1990s ( Sedinger et al. 2007 ). Consequently, 11&percnt; of breeding females must be replaced annually to maintain a stable population. Because 2- and 3-year-old recruits represented 90&percnt; of total recruits into the breeding population, the population should have been increasing when numbers of these recruits exceeded 10&percnt; of total nests. Two- and 3-year old recruits have not exceeded 10&percnt; of nests since 1992 ( Figure 4 ). Numbers of nests at TRC have declined an average of 5&percnt; annually since the mid-1990s, which is approximately consistent with the deficit in numbers of recruits during this study ( Figure 3 ). We note that the long-term decline is unlikely the result of investigator impact because we ruled out such effects elsewhere ( Sedinger 1990 ,  Sedinger et al. 1997 ).  Our results are consistent with the hypothesis that changes in abundance of Arctic foxes in the early 1980s increased the frequency of catastrophic nest failures, which combined with lagged effects of such events has reduced recruitment rates. We hypothesized elsewhere ( Anthony et al. 1991 ) that increased Arctic fox numbers could be the result of anthropogenic food subsidies. Climate change, which is increasing temperatures in the Arctic ( Walsh et al. 2013 ), could also contribute to increased Arctic fox abundance by altering the energy balance of Arctic foxes during winter. Improved understanding of mechanisms underlying the dynamics of Arctic foxes is important to understanding both predator&ndash;prey dynamics and dynamics of geese and their food plants.  The deficit in number of recruits has resulted in a rapidly aging breeding population; mean age of breeding females in the nesting population is now &gt;10 years old (J. S. Sedinger personal observation). Senescence in reproductive success has been detected in Lesser Snow Geese at 8 years of age ( Rockwell et al. 1993 ,  Robertson et al. 1994 ) and in annual survival at 13 years of age ( Koons et al. 2014 ). Senescence in key life-history traits occurs at even younger ages in other long-lived species ( Cam et al. 2002 ,  Boonekamp et al. 2014 ). Preliminary analyses of age-specific breeding probability and survival suggest that both begin to senesce at 11 years of age in Black Brant (J. S. Sedinger personal communication), and adult annual survival is now 5&percnt; lower than before 2000 (A. G. Leach et al. personal communication), consistent with senescent decline in survival in an aging population. Lower adult survival will exacerbate the rate of population decline in the absence of increased recruitment.  In summary, we suggest that relatively infrequent predation events are capable of reducing recruitment for long periods in a long-lived herbivore that depends on grazing lawns for recruitment of offspring into the breeding population. Such lagged effects of predation could potentially occur for other avian herbivore populations that rely on and maintain grazing lawns ( McNaughton 1985 ) or for those that improve vegetation quality following herbivore foraging ( Hik et al. 1991 ,  Person et al. 1998 ). We describe a scenario with relatively sporadic high levels of predation; in scenarios where high levels of predation occur more frequently, the predation itself could be adequate to produce population decline.  We thank the following for assisting with field work: B. Anker, M. Anteau, M. Axelson, J. Bacon, R. Baden, T. Barnett, E. Beers, T. Bentzen, L. Bernstein, M. Blom, K. Bollinger, D. Bos, C. Brown, J. Caikoski, E. Carr, J. Chakuchin, M. Chambers, N. Chelgren, D. Christian, R. Clancy, B. Comstock, R. Crain, J. Curtis, K. Degroot, T. Dixon, W. Don, B. Dugger, A. Earp, D. Eichholz, M. Eichholz, S. Farley, P. Flint, P. Freshman, J. Hall, T. Hande, M. Herzog, J. Hill, D. Hoffman, D. Johnson, T. Jones, Y. Kawaguchi, S. Keane, I. Kharitonov, S. Kharitonov, M. Knoche, P. Kugzruk, C. Lake, L. Lake, J. Lawlor, P. Lemons, P. Lemons II, M. Lindberg, B. Lorenz, D. Maso, G. Moydell, A. Nash, K. Nicholson, A. Nicolai, D. Nicolai, S. Nicolai, D. Nonne, T. Obritchkewitz, W. O'Connell, T. Olson, E. Osnas, J. Otto, H. Panyiak, T. Paragi, A. Perez-Arteaga, B. Person, D. Person, J. Phillipsborn, J. Prop, J. Pratt, C. Pylant, R. Rockwell, T. Rogers, N. Saake, J. Schamber, M. Schreiner, B. Sedinger, M. Shellicans,